                <div class="role">
                  <h4>Cloud DevOps</h4>
                  <span class="role-date">December 2015 - December 2016</span>
                  <p>While working in Global Cloud Engineering, I played a crucial role in transitioning product engineering from a monolithic approach to an iterative method. I introduced Ansible automation extensively to enable the delivery of infrastructure configuration as per the desired state.</p>
                  <p>This standardisation of infrastructure configuration, coupled with measuring the desired state, helped the day two operations team achieve economies of scale, resulting in fewer incidents and better customer satisfaction. Moreover, adopting an iterative delivery approach enabled us to introduce new technology features into the product faster, while making smaller changes helped improve the change risk profile.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="role">
                  <h4>Managed Public Cloud (AWS)</h4>
                  <span class="role-date">September 2016 - December 2016</span>
                  <p>As a team member, I participated in the architecture, engineering, automation, and delivery of a Managed Public Cloud (MPC) offering based on Amazon Web Services (AWS). This MPC service offered centralised management, billing, monitoring, and security solutions that were securely accessible to customers via ServiceNow.</p>
                  <p>My responsibilities included designing the architecture and creating a set of complex CloudFormation templates to deploy standard configurations across AWS accounts. In cases where CloudFormation was insufficient, I created custom "glue" automation using a combination of Ansible and Lambda, with configuration stored in DynamoDB.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="role">
                  <h4>Centralised Control Hub (NSX)</h4>
                  <span class="role-date">December 2015 - September 2016</span>
                  <p>As the technical lead for design, engineering, and delivery, I oversaw a complex NSX for vSphere solution. This solution provided a site-resilient, centralised control hub for thirty-one remote sites or "spokes." To join all the spokes to the hub, we used NSX Edge Services Gateway Site-to-Site VPN tunnels and ensured traffic security using micro-segmentation firewall rules.</p>
                </div>
